title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield 1903 M1
postcontent: This listing is for a Springfield 1903 Mark1 bolt-action rifle.  The firearm is about 80% to 85% condition (very nice for something of this age).  Much of the bluing is still seen on the metal.  There is some small pitting in the metal in a few places (again, to be expected with this age).  This rile was most likely used during WW1 and WW2 by those in service.I have removed the last two digits from the serial number in the photos.  The serial number is 5511XX.  Some argue the lower numbered serial numbers (those below 800,000) are not as durable as the models above 800,000 (in terms of heat treatment on the barrel).  The way I see it, this rifle made it through two world wars, and hundreds of rounds of ammo in my backyard.  To me, a lower serial number only makes an antique firearm that much more appealing.The barrel is stamped with U.S.M.C, and the numbers "1 - 44".  It also has a small encircled letter S under the numbers.  This suggests the barrel was replaced at some time (by Sedgley), and was produced in January of 1944.  It is entirely possible this rifle was custom built for a United States Marine Corp member, but I have yet to find definitive proof (would love to hear your comments).Rifle is chambered in 30-06.  It holds five rounds in the loader.  Bolt action can be switched to pull rounds directly from the loader (until empty); or to lock back after each discharge, allowing rounds to be dropped in by hand, one at a time.  All moving parts are clean, reliable and fully functional.  Trigger and bolt assembly were fully disassembled and oiled (February 22, 2017).  The feed ramp is clean and free of any defects.  The barrel rifling is in excellent condition.Plesae email with any questions.  I will respond to all reasonable offers.
